text.tspan: 1. Floodlights should be used to illuminate haul road crossings where existing light is inadequate.
2. Where no-passing lines are not already in place, they should be added.
The traffc control method selected shall be used in both directions.
4. When a road used exclusively as a haul road is not in use, the haul road shall be closed with Type 3
Barricades and the Flagger symbol signs covered.
The fagger shall follow the procedures provided in Sections 6D.05 and 6D.06.
At night, fagger stations shall be illuminated, except in emergencies.
7. When a road used exclusively as a haul road is not in use, the haul road shall be closed with Type 3
Flash yellow on the main road and fash red on the haul road or be covered, and the Signal
Ahead and STOP HERE ON RED signs shall be covered or hidden from view; or

The temporary traffc control signals shall control both the highway and the haul road and shall
meet the physical display and operational requirements of conventional traffc control signals as
described in Part 4. Traffc control signal timing shall be established by authorized offcials.
Stop lines shall be used on existing highways with temporary traffc control signals.
Existing conficting pavements markings between the stop lines shall be removed. After the
temporary traffc control signal is removed, the stop lines and other temporary pavement markings
shall be removed and the permanent pavement markings restored.
Automated Flagger Assistance Devices (see Section 6L.02) may be used in situations where there is only
one lane of approaching traffc in the direction to be controlled.
12. If actuated signal operation is used (see Item b in Note 7 above) and pedestrian facilities, such as
sidewalks, are present in the area of the haul road crossing, then consideration should be given to
providing pedestrian actuation capability at the temporary traffc control signal to accommodate any
pedestrians who might be depending upon a pedestrian phase to cross the main road.
